06088nam a22009975i 9789048552160DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222022ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485521607 a10.1515/97890485521602doi  a(DE-B1597)626069  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aND623.T7 7aART0090002bisacsh04a759.5223/eng/2022071800aTitian's Allegory of Marriage :bNew Approaches /ced. by Daniel Unger. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (266 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aVisual and Material Culture, 1300 –1700 ;v3700tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Plates and Figures -- t1. Introduction: Poetic License -- t2. Love, Beauty, and the Human Body as a Reflection of the Divine -- t3. Amorosa visione: Titian’s Allegory of Marriage and the Poetry of the Half-length Format -- t4. The Arms and Armour of Titian’s Allegory of Marriage -- t5. ‘Un disio sol d’eterna gloria e fama’: A Literary Approach to Titian’s Allegory -- t6. Psyche, Venus, Ceres and Their Friends: Titian’s Remixes -- t7. Art and the Double Meaning of Reflection in Titian’s Allegory of Marriage -- t8. Titian’s Allegory of Marriage as an ‘Allegory of Peace’ -- t9. Vision and Touch in the Allegory of Marriage -- t10. Of Crystal Orbs and Divinatory Mirrors : The Vicissitudes of Pregnancy and Artistic Agency in Titian’s Allegory of Marriage -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book offers nine new approaches toward a single work of art, Titian’s Allegory of Marriage or Allegory of Alfonso d’Avalos, dated to 1530/5. In earlier references, the painting was named simply Allegory, alluding to its enigmatic nature. The work follows in a tradition of such ambiguous Venetian paintings as Giovanni Bellini’s Sacred Allegory and Giorgione’s Tempest. Throughout the years, Titian’s Allegory has engendered a range of diverse interpretations. Art historians such as Hans Tietze, Erwin Panofsky, Walter Friedlaender, and Louis Hourticq, to mention only a few, promoted various explanations. This book offers novel approaches and suggests new meanings toward a further understanding of this somewhat abstruse painting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aEuropean history: Renaissance. 4aHistory of art. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aItalian. 4aPaintings and painting. 4aRenaissance style. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh  aTitian, Allegory, Marriage, Alfonso d'Avalos.1 aBenninga, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoannides, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKodera, Sergius, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKravitz-Lurie, Esthy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehman, Geoff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPardo, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRees, Valery, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUnger, Daniel M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUnger, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWatts, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076709408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2022 Part 2z978311076700108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Architecture and Design 2022z9783110992793oZDB-23-DAD08iTitle is part of e